/*
Q: What is the purpose of the shouldComponentUpdate lifecycle method?
A: The shouldComponentUpdate lifecycle method is used to optimize performance by preventing unnecessary re-renders.
It is called before the render method and allows you to return false to prevent the component from re-rendering when the props or state change.
This can be useful for improving performance in components that receive frequent updates but do not need to re-render every time.
*/
// An example of using shouldComponentUpdate:
class MyComponent extends React.Component {
    shouldComponentUpdate(nextProps, nextState) {
        return nextProps.value !== this.props.value;
    }
    render() {
        return <p>{this.props.value}</p>;
    }
}

/*
Q: What is the purpose of the componentWillUnmount lifecycle method?
A: The componentWillUnmount lifecycle method is called just before a component is unmounted and destroyed.
This method is used for cleanup tasks, such as invalidating timers, canceling network requests, or cleaning up subscriptions that were created in componentDidMount.
It is important to use componentWillUnmount to prevent memory leaks and ensure that any resources used by the component are properly released when the component is removed from the DOM.
*/
// An example of using componentWillUnmount:
class MyComponent
    extends React.Component {
    componentWillUnmount() {
        console.log('Component will unmount');
    }
    render() {
        return <p>My Component</p>;
    }
}

