*/

/*
Q: What is the purpose of setState in React?
A: setState is a method used to update the state of a component and trigger a re-render of the component with the new state.
When you call setState, React schedules an update to the component's state and re-renders the component with the updated state.
It's important to note that setState is asynchronous, so you should not rely on the state being updated immediately after calling setState.
A common pattern is to use the callback function of setState to perform actions after the state has been updated.
*/
// An example of using setState:
class MyComponent extends React.Component {
    constructor(props) {
        super(props);
        this.state = { count: 0 };
    }
    incrementCount = () => {
        this.setState({ count: this.state.count + 1 });
    }
    render() {
        return (
        <div>
            <p>Count: {this.state.count}</p>
            <button onClick={this.incrementCount}>Increment</button>
            </div>
        );
    }
}

/*
Q: Can you explain the concept of lifting state up in React?
A: Lifting state up is a pattern where you move the state from a child component to a common parent component.
This allows multiple child components to share and synchronize the same state through the parent component.
For example, if two sibling components need to share the same data, you can lift the state up to their common parent and pass it down as props to both components.
*/
// An example of lifting state:
class ParentComponent extends React.Component {
  constructor(props) {
    super(props);
    this.state = { sharedData: 'Hello' };
  }
}

class ChildComponent extends React.Component {
  render() {
    return <p>{this.props.sharedData}</p>;
  }
}

/*
Q: What is the useEffect hook in React?
A: The useEffect hook is a function that allows you to perform side effects in functional components.
It is used to handle tasks like data fetching, subscriptions, or manually changing the DOM.
The useEffect hook takes a function as an argument and runs it after the component renders.
You can also specify dependencies for the effect, so it only runs when certain values change.
A common use case for useEffect is to fetch data from an API when the component mounts.
*/
// An example of using useEffect:
function MyComponent() {
    const [data, setData] = useState(null);
    useEffect(() => {
        fetch('https://api.example.com/data')
            .then(response => response.json())
            .then(data => setData(data));
    }, []);
    return (
        <div>
            {data ? <p>{data.message}</p> : <p>Loading...</p>}
        </div>
    );
}

/*
Q: What is the purpose of the useContext hook?
A: The useContext hook is used to access the value of a context in a functional component.
Context provides a way to pass data through the component tree without having to pass props down manually at every level.
The useContext hook allows you to consume the context value directly in a functional component, making it easier to share data across components without prop drilling.
*/
// An example of using useContext:
const MyContext = React.createContext();
function MyComponent() {
    const value = useContext(MyContext);
    return <p>{value}</p>;
}

/*
Q: What is the purpose of the useReducer hook?
A: The useReducer hook is an alternative to useState for managing state in functional components.
It is used when you have complex state logic that involves multiple sub-values or when the next state depends on the previous one.
useReducer takes a reducer function and an initial state, and returns the current state and a dispatch function to update the state.
*/
// An example of using useReducer:
function reducer(state, action) {
    switch (action.type) {
        case 'increment':
            return { count: state.count + 1 };
        case 'decrement':
            return { count: state.count - 1 };
        default:
            throw new Error();
    }
}

function Counter() {
    const [state, dispatch] = useReducer(reducer, { count: 0 });
    return (
        <div>
            Count: {state.count}
            <button onClick={() => dispatch({ type: 'increment' })}>+</button>
            <button onClick={() => dispatch({ type: 'decrement' })}>-</button>
        </div>
    );
}

/*
Q: What is the purpose of the useMemo hook?
A: The useMemo hook is used to memoize a value so that it is only recalculated when its dependencies change.
This can improve performance by preventing expensive calculations on every render.
*/
// An example of using useMemo:
function MyComponent({ a, b }) {
    const memoizedValue = useMemo(() => {
        return a + b;
    }, [a, b]);
    return <p>{memoizedValue}</p>;
}

/*
Q: What is the concept of error boundaries in React?
A: Error boundaries are React components that catch and log JavaScript errors in the component tree, displaying a fallback UI or taking appropriate action.
Error boundaries are implemented using class components and the componentDidCatch lifecycle method.
They help prevent the entire application from crashing when an error occurs in a specific part of the UI.
*/
// An example of an error boundary:
class ErrorBoundary extends React.Component {
    constructor(props) {
        super(props);
        this.state = { hasError: false };
    }

    componentDidCatch(error, info) {
        this.setState({ hasError: true });
        console.error(error, info);
    }

    render() {
        if (this.state.hasError) {
            return <h1>Something went wrong.</h1>;
        }
        return this.props.children;
    }
}

/*
Q: What is the significance of the useCallback hook?
A: The useCallback hook is used to memoize a function so that it is only recreated when its dependencies change.
This can improve performance by preventing unnecessary re-creations of functions on every render.
*/
// An example of using useCallback:
function MyComponent({ onClick }) {
    const memoizedOnClick = useCallback(() => {
        onClick();
    }, [onClick]);
    return <button onClick={memoizedOnClick}>Click me</button>;
}

/*
Q: How does React handle code splitting?
A: React handles code splitting using dynamic import() and React.lazy.
This allows code to split into smaller chunks that can load on demand, improving performance of the application by reducing the initial load time.
Use React.lazy to define a component that is loaded lazily, and wrap it in a Suspense component to provide a fallback UI while it is loading.
*/

/*
Q: What is the concept of React Suspense?
A: Suspense is a feature that allows rendering of a component to be deferred until a condition is met (data being loaded or a component being lazy-loaded).
Suspense works with React's concurrent mode to provide a better user experience by showing fallback content while waiting for the main content to load.
You can use the Suspense component to wrap parts of your UI that may take time to load, and provide a fallback UI to display in the meantime.
*/

/*
Q: What is the concept of React Lazy Loading?
A: Lazy loading is a technique that allows you to load components or resources only when they are needed, rather than loading everything upfront.
In React, you can use the React.lazy function to define a component that is loaded lazily.
This can improve the performance of your application by reducing the initial load time and allowing users to access content faster.
*/
// An example of code splitting using Suspense and React Lazy Loading:
const LazyComponent = React.lazy(() => import('./LazyComponent'));
function MyComponent() {
    return (
        <Suspense fallback={<div>Loading...</div>}>
            <LazyComponent />
        </Suspense>
    );
}

